# Browser sign-in — OAuth2 Authorization Code + PKCE, end to end, no setup.
#
# This runs the full interactive grant against a bundled local identity provider,
# so you can see the browser round-trip with zero accounts, client IDs, or
# secrets. lazyhttp opens your browser to the demo /authorize page; you click
# "Approve"; it catches the redirect on a localhost listener and exchanges the
# code for a token, then calls the demo resource with it.
#
#     just demo-server        # start the local demo IdP on :9000 (one terminal)
#     just demo-browser       # or: lazyhttp --env local example.browser.http
#
# The demo issues a refresh token, so the token is saved to tokens.json and a
# second run renews silently without reopening the browser. Run in the TUI (only
# the TUI opens a browser); headless `lazyhttp run` reuses that saved login.
#
# For a real provider (Google), see the Authorization Code section of
# docs/http-format.md — same config shape, pointed at the provider's endpoints.

### Browser sign-in, then call a protected resource with the token
# @group Browser auth
# @name Browser sign-in
GET {{api}}/me
Authorization: Bearer {{$auth.token("browser")}}
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.saw_authorization contains Bearer
